<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Duty to Have Regard to Growth</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="OLE_LINK8"></a><a name="OLE_LINK9"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Cabinet Office – Supplementary written evidence</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Duty to Have Regard to Growth</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Information on regulators in scope of clauses 58 to 61 of the Draft Deregulation Bill</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Regulatory functions</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Clause 59 of the Bill provides that those regulatory functions which will be in scope of the growth duty will be set out in an affirmative Statutory Instrument (SI) after enactment. The Clause also provides that the relevant parties must be consulted.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Clause refers to ‘regulatory functions’ rather than regulators as this level of detail is needed to ensure the correct aspects of a regulator’s role are included in the duty. However for simplicity we are referring to the regulators in scope here and in practice the SI may list regulators as well as functions.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Appendix A to this document contains the definition of a regulatory function already supplied to the Committee.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Regulators in scope</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">I</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">n the Government response to the consultation</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> we stated that we envisaged that the non-economic regulatory functions of the following regulators would be in scope. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">This is the reference list of regulators that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">the Government has</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline"> already agreed to be in scope following relevant consultation.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 2pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Animal Health and Veterinary Laboratory Agency </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 2pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Anim</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">als in Science Regulation Unit</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 2pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">British Hallmarking Council </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 2pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Care Quality Commission </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 2pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Charity Commission for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">England</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Wales</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 2pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Civil Aviation Authority</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 2pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Claims Management Regulation Unit </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 2pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Coal Authority </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 2pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Companies House </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 2pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Disclosure and Barring Service </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 2pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Drinking Water Inspectorate </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 2pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Driver and Vehicle Licensing Agency </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 2pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Driving Standards Agency </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 2pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Employment Agency Standards Directorate </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 2pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">English Heritage </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 2pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Environment Agency </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 2pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Equality and Human Rights Commission </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 2pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Financial Reporting Council </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 2pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Fish Health Inspectorate, Centre for Environment, Fisheries and Aquaculture Science </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 2pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Food and Environment Research Agency </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 2pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Food Standards Agency </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 2pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Forestry Commission </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 2pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Gambling Commission </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 2pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Gangmasters Licensing Authority </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 2pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">General Lighthouse Authorities</span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 2pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Groceries Code Adjudicator </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 2pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Health and Safety Executive </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 2pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Highways Agency </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 2pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">HM Revenue and Customs (Money Laundering Regulations and National Minimum Wage) </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 2pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Homes and Communities Agency </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 2pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Human Fertilisation and Embryology Authority </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 2pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Human Tissue Authority </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 2pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Information Commissioner’s Office </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 2pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Insolvency Service including Insolvency Practitioner Unit </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 2pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Intellectual Property Office </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 2pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Legal Services Board </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 2pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Marine Management Organisation </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 2pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Maritime and Coastguard Agency </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 2pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Medicines and Healthcare Products Regulatory Agency </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 2pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">National Counter Terrorism Security Office </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 2pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">National Measurement Office </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 2pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Natural </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">England</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 2pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Office for Fair Access </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 2pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Office for Nuclear Regulation </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 2pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Office for Standards in Education, Children’s Services and Skills </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 2pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Office of the Regulator of Community Interest Companies </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 2pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Professional Standards Authority </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 2pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Rural Payments Agency </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 2pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Security Industry Authority </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 2pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Solicitors Regulation Authority </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 2pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Sports Grounds Safety Authority </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 2pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Traffic Commissioners </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 2pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Vehicle and Operator Services Agency </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 2pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Vehicle Certification Agency </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 2pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Veterinary Medicines Directorate </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">In discussion</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Government </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">consulted on the application of the growth duty in respect of most regulators</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> listed above</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">but we are now engaging with a number of additional </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">bodies and relevant trade </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">bodies</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to explore whether they should be brought into scope.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We are currently considering whether </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">a wider number of bodies that regulate professionals </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">under regulatory functions conferred on them by Parliament such as</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the Architects Registration Board</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the chartered institutes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> be included. In addition, we are aware of three further regulators that have relevant functions that should/could be in scope of the duty - namely Ofqual, the Office of Rail Regulation and Monitor.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Finally, we are considering whether</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> statutory regulatory functions of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Advertising Standards Authority (ASA) should be in sco</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">pe of the duty, in line with</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> feedback recei</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ved through the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> consultation</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Exceptions</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The clauses as drafted would allow the duty to be applied to any person or body exercising </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">non-economic </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">regulatory functions; nobody has been excluded on the face of the Bill.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Whilst there are no specific exclusions, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">it is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">not</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> intended that economic regulators will be included in the SI, for the following reasons: </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:8.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Economic regulators are bodies that are set up to correct the market failure of natural monopoly and therefore protect consumers and promote efficiency</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:8.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">This typically happens in infrastructure areas such as electricity and gas, water and communications</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:8.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Economic regulation is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">very</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> different to non-economic regulation, which does not seek to correct for monopoly power or efficiency in a market</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:8.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">However, the distinction is not absolute as there are bodies that undertake both economic and non-economic regulatory functions</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> such as the CAA, ORR and Monitor.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:8.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The regulators deemed to be economic regulators and thus outside of the scope of the duty are Ofcom, Ofgem, Ofwat and the Northern Ireland Utilities Regulator.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:8.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The newly created CMA is likely to also fall squarely within the definition of an economic regulator for these purposes.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:8.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Economic regulators’ primary focus is on the efficient operation of a market. Their existing duties drive growth through the promotion of competition and investment.  </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Government is seeking to ensure a comprehensive coverage of the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">growth duty</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to non-economic regulatory functions. Where a person or a body conducts non-economic regulatory activity we believe these functions should be in scope of the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">growth duty</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">However there are those exercising non-economic regulatory functions</span><a name="_ftnref5"></a><a href="#_ftn5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> that for various reasons should not be in scope of the growth duty at present:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">The Financial Conduct Authority and the Prudential Regulation Authority</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The new financial services regulators, the Financial Conduct Authority (FCA) and Prudential Regulation Authority (PRA), were recently given statutory growth duties through the Financial Services Act 2012, which require them to have regard to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">‘the desirability of sustainable growth in the economy of the United Kingdom in the medium or long term’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">They are also required to have regard to the principle of proportionality. The Government believes these duties are appropriately framed for regulators of financial services, given the nature of financial services markets and their role in the economy, while being sufficiently similar in intent to this growth duty to remove any necessity to apply it to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> their non-economic regulatory functions</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">The Pensions Regulator</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In the Budget 2013, the Chancellor of the Exchequer announced the Government’s intention to provide the Pensions Regulator (tPR) with a new objective to support scheme funding arrangements that are compatible with sustainable growth for the sponsoring employer. This announcement followed a call for evidence earlier this year by the Department for Work and Pensions (DWP) on whether a new employer-focused objective is appropriate. The majority of respondents to that call for evidence favoured such a change, recognising the importance of strong, healthy employers to defined benefit pension schemes. The new objective is therefore included in the Pensions Bill, currently before Parliament. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Given that there is already a growth-focused objective focusing on key tPR functions before Parliament, the Government has decided on balance not to apply the new growth duty to tPR for now. The Government considers that it is important to allow the new tPR objective to complete its passage through the Parliamentary process and to bed in before considering further the need for additional duties. Should it become apparent that the application of a growth duty to tPR’s other functions is a sensible and proportionate change the Government will include tPR within scope of the growth duty. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Immigration functions (specifically the immigration-related</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">regulatory enforcement functions of the Home Office)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Immigration functions now fall within the full Home Office portfolio.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> The Home Office’s priorities are the interlinked objectives of ensuring our national security and a safe, cohesive society. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The management of the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">UK</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">’s border and migration system is key to supporting these objectives.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Where possible, and balanced against the wider security interests of the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">UK</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, migration initiatives and policies will support economic enrichment.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> In addition, the immigration system is subject to high volumes of litigation.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> The vast majority of judicial review applications, for example, are immigration cases (over 70% in 2011).</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> We believe the risk of vexatious challenges concerning the application of the growth duty is therefore higher than in relation to other </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">regulatory functions and the Government has therefore decided to exclude immigration functions from the growth duty for the time being.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">There is precedent for this - in the Equality Act 2010 immigration functions were excluded from similar duties in order to limit exposure to legal risk. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:right"><br style="page-break-before:always; clear:both" /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Appendix A</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Information on </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">the definition of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> a regulatory function for the purposes of clauses 58 to 61 of the Draft Deregulation Bill</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Clause 61 of the Draft Deregulation Bill defines a regulatory function to which the duty to have regard to the des</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">irability of economic growth can apply.  It states:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:BookAntiquaParliamentary-Bold; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">“ 61 Sections 58 to 60: interpretation</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-indent:18pt"><span style="font-family:BookAntiquaParliamentary; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">(1) In sections 58 to 60, “regulatory function” means:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-indent:72pt"><span style="font-family:BookAntiquaParliamentary; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">(a) a function under or by virtue of an Act or subordinate legislation of</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:BookAntiquaParliamentary; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">imposing requirements, restrictions or conditions, or setting standards</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-indent:72pt"><span style="font-family:BookAntiquaParliamentary; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">or giving guidance, in relation to an activity; or</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-indent:72pt"><span style="font-family:BookAntiquaParliamentary; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">(b) a function which relates to the securing of compliance with, or the</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-indent:72pt"><span style="font-family:BookAntiquaParliamentary; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">enforcement of, requirements, restrictions, conditions, standards or</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-indent:72pt"><span style="font-family:BookAntiquaParliamentary; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">guidance which, under or by virtue of an Act or subordinate legislation,</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-indent:72pt"><span style="font-family:BookAntiquaParliamentary; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">relate to an activity.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-indent:72pt"><span style="font-family:BookAntiquaParliamentary; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-indent:18pt"><span style="font-family:BookAntiquaParliamentary; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">(2) </span><span style="font-family:BookAntiquaParliamentary; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">              </span><span style="font-family:BookAntiquaParliamentary; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">In subsection (1)(a) and (b) the references to a function include a function</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:BookAntiquaParliamentary; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">exercisable by or on behalf of the Crown.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:BookAntiquaParliamentary; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-indent:18pt"><span style="font-family:BookAntiquaParliamentary; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">(3) In subsection (1)(a) and (b) the references to an activity include:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:BookAntiquaParliamentary; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">(a) providing goods and services; and</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:BookAntiquaParliamentary; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">(b) employing or offering employment to a person.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:BookAntiquaParliamentary; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:BookAntiquaParliamentary; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">(4) </span><span style="font-family:BookAntiquaParliamentary; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">              </span><span style="font-family:BookAntiquaParliamentary; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">In sections 59 and 60, “Minister of the Crown” has the same meaning as in the Ministers of the Crown Act 1975.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-indent:18pt"><span style="font-family:BookAntiquaParliamentary; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-indent:18pt"><span style="font-family:BookAntiquaParliamentary; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">(5) </span><span style="font-family:BookAntiquaParliamentary; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">              </span><span style="font-family:BookAntiquaParliamentary; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">In this section, “subordinate legislation” has the same meaning as in the</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:BookAntiquaParliamentary; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Interpretation Act 1978.</span><span style="font-family:BookAntiquaParliamentary; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:BookAntiquaParliamentary; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">” </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:BookAntiquaParliamentary; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">This definition has been adopted to ensure </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the policy objectives are achieved and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the duty to have regard to growth is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">applied </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">all </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">regulator</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">y functions to which it would be appropriate. It is also consistent with the existing definition that underpins the statutory code of practice for regulators (Regulators’ Compliance Code). The definition above does not expressly exclude economic regulatory functions; however the Government is clear that this duty is designed to apply to non-economic regulatory functions, rather than economic regulatory functions.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Economic r</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">egulatory functions</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 12pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">UK</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, economic regulation has typically been introduced in areas where network effects and/or economies of scale create circumstances - such as natural monopolies – which limit the prospects for effective competition. </span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 12pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The aim of economic regulation is to create a system of incentives and penalties that replicate the outcomes of competition in terms of consumer prices, quality and investment and puts the protection of consumers’ interests at its heart. </span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 12pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Typically, economic regulators oversee infrastructure sectors such as gas and electricity (Ofgem), Water (Ofwat) and Communications (Ofcom). Economic regulation in these sectors caps the prices that dominant companies can charge in order to promote efficiency and fairness, while providing them a return on their assets and investments. </span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 12pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Economic regulation has also been applied to non-infrastructure sectors where similar institutional arrangements apply, such as the future economic regulation of healthcare services (Monitor).</span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 12pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Economic regulation is a qualitatively different form of regulation to non-economic regulation (such as that undertaken by regulators such as the Health and Safety Executive or the Environment Agency) which do </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">not </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">correct for the market failure of natural monopoly </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">or </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">promote efficiency within a market. </span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 12pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">However t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">he distinction is not absolute. There are some bodies that conduct a mix of both economic and non-economic regulatory functions (for example safety), such as the Civil Aviation Authority. Government is clear that it aims to ensure that as wide a range of non-economic regulatory functions </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">as possible are</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> captured as part of the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">gr</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">owth </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">d</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">uty. It therefore is seeking to apply the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">g</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">rowth </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">d</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">uty to the non-economic regulatory functions of such bodies, where the level of non-economic regulatory activity is significant.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">Better Regulation Delivery Office; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt; font-style:italic">Government Response: Non-economic Regulators: Duty to Have Regard to Growth</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">; July 2013 </span><a href="http://www.bis.gov.uk/assets/brdo/docs/publications-2013/13-1018-growth-consultation-response.pdf"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.bis.gov.uk/assets/brdo/docs/publications-2013/13-1018-growth-consultation-response.pdf</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">The duty will not apply to the project licensing decisions of the Animals in Science Regulation Unit</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">.  The industry concerned has specifically asked that project licensing decisions be omitted to avoid harm to the industry, as such decisions assess the level of detriment to animal welfare against the potential benefits of a project. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn3"></a><a href="#_ftnref3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">The duty will not apply to the economic regulatory functions of the Civil Aviation Authority</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn4"></a><a href="#_ftnref4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt"> Including Trinity House Lighthouse Service, the Northern Lighthouse Board and the Commissioner of Irish Lights (in respect of its regulatory functions in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">Northern Ireland</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn5"></a><a href="#_ftnref5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> The Serious Organised Crime Agency (SOCA) was included in the original consultation on the growth duty. However we have since clarified that they are a police function and it would not therefore be appropriate to bring SOCA within scope of the growth duty for regulatory functions.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p></body></html>